{
  "What is bioethics?": "",
  "The study of ethical issues arising from advances in biology and medicine": "",
  "The laboratory techniques used in genetic engineering": "",
  "A branch of chemistry focused on biological molecules": "",
  "The study of how living organisms evolve over time": "",
  "Bioethics examines the moral questions raised by breakthroughs in biology and medicine — including genetic engineering, cloning, stem cell research, organ transplantation, and end-of-life care. It draws on philosophy, law, theology, and social science to establish ethical guidelines for research and clinical practice. Bioethics became a formal discipline after scandals like the Tuskegee study revealed the need for systematic ethical oversight.": "",
  "What is informed consent?": "",
  "A doctor's permission for a patient to leave the hospital": "",
  "A patient's or research subject's voluntary agreement to a procedure or study after being fully informed of the risks, benefits, and alternatives": "",
  "Signing a form without reading it because you trust the doctor": "",
  "A legal document that prevents lawsuits regardless of what happens": "",
  "Informed consent is a cornerstone of bioethics. It requires that a competent individual receives clear information about what will be done, the potential risks and benefits, alternatives available, and the right to withdraw at any time — and then voluntarily agrees. It is legally and ethically required for medical procedures, clinical trials, and research participation. Informed consent protects patient autonomy.": "",
  "What is genetic privacy?": "",
  "The inability of scientists to read DNA sequences": "",
  "Keeping all genetic research results secret from the public": "",
  "The ability of genes to hide from the immune system": "",
  "The right of individuals to control access to their personal genetic information": "",
  "Genetic privacy refers to an individual's right to keep their genetic information confidential and control who has access to it. As genetic testing becomes widespread (through services like 23andMe and clinical genomic sequencing), concerns have grown about misuse by employers, insurers, law enforcement, and others. In the U.S., GINA (2008) prohibits genetic discrimination in health insurance and employment.": "",
  "What is the difference between reproductive cloning and therapeutic cloning?": "",
  "There is no difference — both terms mean the same thing": "",
  "Reproductive cloning creates a new organism; therapeutic cloning creates stem cells for medical treatment without producing a whole organism": "",
  "Reproductive cloning is natural; therapeutic cloning is artificial": "",
  "Reproductive cloning uses plants; therapeutic cloning uses animals": "",
  "Reproductive cloning aims to create a genetically identical organism (like Dolly the sheep via SCNT). Therapeutic cloning uses the same SCNT technique but stops at the blastocyst stage to harvest embryonic stem cells for medical research or treatment — no complete organism is produced. Therapeutic cloning is supported by those who see medical potential in patient-matched stem cells, while reproductive cloning in humans is banned virtually worldwide.": "",
  "What is the Belmont Report, and why is it significant?": "",
  "A 1979 document establishing three core ethical principles for human research: respect for persons, beneficence, and justice": "",
  "A scientific paper proving that cloning is safe for humans": "",
  "A report concluding that stem cell research has no ethical concerns": "",
  "A law banning all genetic engineering in the United States": "",
  "The Belmont Report was created in response to ethical abuses like the Tuskegee Syphilis Study. It established three foundational principles: (1) Respect for persons — individuals should be treated as autonomous agents and those with diminished autonomy deserve protection; (2) Beneficence — maximize benefits and minimize harm; (3) Justice — distribute the burdens and benefits of research fairly. Every Institutional Review Board (IRB) in the U.S. uses these principles to evaluate research proposals.": "",
  "What is an Institutional Review Board (IRB)?": "",
  "A hospital department that treats patients with genetic diseases": "",
  "A government agency that funds all scientific research": "",
  "A court that decides patent disputes over genetic inventions": "",
  "A committee that reviews and approves research involving human subjects to ensure ethical standards are met": "",
  "An IRB is an ethics committee that reviews all proposed research involving human subjects to ensure compliance with federal regulations and ethical principles from the Belmont Report. IRBs evaluate risks vs. benefits, informed consent procedures, participant selection, and data privacy protections. No federally funded research on human subjects can proceed without IRB approval.": "",
  "What does GINA (Genetic Information Nondiscrimination Act) protect against?": "",
  "Discrimination by employers and health insurers based on an individual's genetic information": "",
  "The patenting of any human gene sequences": "",
  "The use of CRISPR in any medical research": "",
  "All forms of genetic testing in the United States": "",
  "GINA, enacted in 2008, has two main titles: Title I prohibits health insurers from using genetic information to make coverage or premium decisions; Title II prohibits employers from using genetic information in hiring, firing, or promotion decisions. However, GINA does not cover life insurance, disability insurance, or long-term care insurance — a gap that remains controversial.": "",
  "What is the main ethical concern with embryonic stem cell (ESC) research?": "",
  "There is no ethical concern — everyone agrees ESC research is acceptable": "",
  "ESCs are too dangerous to use in any medical treatment": "",
  "Harvesting ESCs requires destroying human embryos, raising questions about the moral status of embryos": "",
  "ESC research has never produced any useful results": "",
  "Embryonic stem cells are pluripotent — they can develop into any cell type in the body. However, to obtain ESCs, scientists must destroy a blastocyst (a 5-day-old embryo of ~100 cells). Those who believe life begins at conception consider this equivalent to taking a human life; supporters argue that blastocysts lack sentience and that the medical potential justifies ESC research. iPSCs (induced pluripotent stem cells) offer a partial ethical workaround.": "",
  "What ethical principle does germline editing (editing DNA in eggs, sperm, or embryos) most directly challenge?": "",
  "Nonmaleficence — germline editing is guaranteed to be harmful": "",
  "Beneficence — germline editing can never benefit anyone": "",
  "Consent — future generations who inherit the changes cannot agree to or refuse them": "",
  "Justice — germline editing would be equally available to everyone": "",
  "Germline editing changes DNA that is passed to all future descendants. Unlike somatic gene therapy (which affects only the treated individual), germline modifications are permanent and heritable. The edited individuals' descendants cannot consent to these permanent genetic changes. Additionally, off-target effects could introduce harmful mutations that propagate through generations. In 2018, He Jiankui's editing of human embryos (the 'CRISPR babies' case) was widely condemned for violating this principle.": "",
  "What was the Tuskegee Syphilis Study, and why is it significant in bioethics?": "",
  "A 40-year U.S. government study that left African American men with syphilis untreated, leading directly to the creation of the Belmont Report and modern research ethics": "",
  "A study that demonstrated informed consent was unnecessary for research": "",
  "A successful clinical trial that proved penicillin could cure syphilis": "",
  "An unrelated historical event with no impact on modern research regulations": "",
  "From 1932 to 1972, the U.S. Public Health Service studied untreated syphilis in 399 African American men in Tuskegee, Alabama. Participants were told they were being treated, but received no treatment — even after penicillin became the standard cure in 1947. The study violated every ethical principle: no informed consent, deliberate harm, and targeted a vulnerable population. Its exposure led directly to the Belmont Report (1979) and the establishment of IRBs to oversee human subjects research.": "",
  "In bioethics, what does the term 'autonomy' mean?": "",
  "The right of individuals to make their own informed decisions about their bodies and medical care without coercion": "",
  "The obligation of doctors to always choose the most aggressive treatment": "",
  "The ability of robots to perform surgery without human oversight": "",
  "The principle that government should control all medical decisions": "",
  "Autonomy is one of the four core principles of biomedical ethics (along with beneficence, nonmaleficence, and justice). It holds that competent individuals have the right to self-determination — to make decisions about their own bodies, health care, and participation in research. Respecting autonomy means providing full information, avoiding coercion, and honoring a patient's right to refuse treatment.": "",
  "What does the bioethical term 'beneficence' refer to?": "",
  "The right to refuse any medical treatment": "",
  "The obligation to act in ways that promote the well-being of others and maximize benefits": "",
  "The practice of performing only the least invasive procedures": "",
  "The duty to distribute medical resources equally to all patients": "",
  "Beneficence is the ethical duty to do good — to take actions that benefit patients or research subjects. In medicine, this means choosing treatments that improve outcomes, conducting research that advances knowledge, and weighing benefits against risks. Beneficence can sometimes conflict with autonomy, such as when a patient refuses a treatment that a doctor believes would be beneficial.": "",
  "What does 'nonmaleficence' mean in bioethics?": "",
  "The principle that all medical research should be publicly funded": "",
  "The requirement to always seek the most advanced technology": "",
  "The obligation to 'do no harm' — to avoid causing unnecessary injury or suffering to patients or research subjects": "",
  "The belief that natural remedies are always safer than pharmaceuticals": "",
  "Nonmaleficence ('do no harm') is related to but distinct from beneficence. While beneficence requires actively doing good, nonmaleficence requires avoiding inflicting harm. In practice, many medical interventions carry risks (e.g., chemotherapy causes side effects), so the principle is often applied as a balancing test: the potential benefits must outweigh the potential harms. The phrase 'primum non nocere' (first, do no harm) is attributed to the Hippocratic tradition.": "",
  "In bioethics, what does the principle of 'justice' require?": "",
  "Punishing researchers who fail to find cures for diseases": "",
  "Requiring all patients to participate in clinical trials": "",
  "Ensuring that only wealthy patients receive experimental treatments": "",
  "Fair distribution of the benefits and burdens of medical research and healthcare among all groups in society": "",
  "Justice in bioethics addresses fairness and equity. It asks: Who benefits from research? Who bears the risks? Are resources distributed equitably? The Belmont Report identified justice as a core principle because historically, vulnerable populations (prisoners, minorities, the poor) bore disproportionate research burdens while wealthier groups reaped the benefits. Justice requires equitable participant selection, fair access to treatments, and protection of vulnerable groups.": "",
  "What does the term 'gene drive' mean in the context of bioethics debates?": "",
  "A natural process by which genes randomly mutate over generations": "",
  "A genetic engineering technology that biases inheritance so that a modified gene spreads through an entire wild population, raising ecological and ethical concerns": "",
  "A computer program that predicts a person's genetic disease risk": "",
  "A type of car engine powered by genetically modified biofuel": "",
  "Gene drives use CRISPR to create genetic elements that are inherited by nearly 100% of offspring (rather than the normal 50%). This allows an engineered trait to spread rapidly through a wild population. Proposed applications include making mosquitoes unable to transmit malaria or making invasive species sterile. Bioethical concerns include irreversibility (once released, a gene drive cannot easily be recalled), potential ecological disruption, and the question of who has the right to alter an entire species.": "",
  "What does the term 'xenotransplantation' mean?": "",
  "Replacing a damaged organ with an artificial mechanical device": "",
  "Transplanting organs between identical twins": "",
  "Growing a new organ from a patient's own stem cells in a lab": "",
  "Transplanting organs or tissues from one species into another, such as a pig heart into a human": "",
  "Xenotransplantation (xeno = foreign/stranger) involves transplanting living cells, tissues, or organs from one species to another. The most researched approach uses genetically modified pigs as organ donors for humans. In 2022, the first pig-to-human heart transplant (David Bennett) demonstrated feasibility but also highlighted risks: cross-species viral transmission (PERVs), immune rejection, and animal welfare concerns.": "",
  "In bioethics, what are 'incidental findings'?": "",
  "Minor side effects of approved medications": "",
  "Planned outcomes of a carefully designed experiment": "",
  "Unexpected results discovered during genetic testing or medical imaging that were not the original purpose of the test": "",
  "Accidental contamination of laboratory samples": "",
  "Incidental (or secondary) findings are unanticipated discoveries made during testing — for example, a whole-genome sequence ordered for cancer risk might also reveal Huntington's disease risk or non-paternity. The ACMG recommends reporting medically actionable incidental findings (like BRCA mutations), but non-medical findings (like non-paternity) create ethical dilemmas about the duty to disclose vs. potential harm from unwanted information.": "",
  "What does the term 'moral status' mean in bioethics discussions about embryos, fetuses, or animals?": "",
  "The organism's position in the phylogenetic tree of life": "",
  "The legal classification of an organism under federal law": "",
  "Whether an entity is considered to have rights, interests, or value that impose ethical obligations on others": "",
  "Whether an organism can survive outside a laboratory environment": "",
  "Moral status determines how an entity should be treated ethically. A being with full moral status has rights that cannot be violated. Debates about the moral status of embryos drive the stem cell and abortion controversies; debates about animal moral status drive animal research ethics. Different frameworks assign moral status based on sentience, genetic humanity, potentiality, or relational properties.": "",
  "What does the term 'scientific integrity' refer to in the context of bioethics?": "",
  "The physical security of a research laboratory building": "",
  "The structural stability of DNA molecules in laboratory conditions": "",
  "The ethical obligation of researchers to conduct and report their work honestly, transparently, and without fabrication or plagiarism": "",
  "The amount of funding a scientist receives for their research": "",
  "Scientific integrity encompasses honesty in data collection and reporting, proper attribution of others' work, transparent methodology, and avoidance of fabrication, falsification, and plagiarism (FFP). High-profile violations include the Hwang Woo-suk stem cell fraud (2004-05) and Andrew Wakefield's fabricated autism-vaccine link. Integrity is maintained through peer review, replication, data sharing, and institutional oversight.": "",
  "What does the term 'right to try' mean in bioethics?": "",
  "A patient's right to try multiple doctors before committing to one": "",
  "Laws allowing terminally ill patients to access experimental drugs that have passed Phase I trials but are not yet FDA-approved": "",
  "The right of scientists to conduct any experiment without ethical review": "",
  "The requirement for all patients to attempt physical therapy before surgery": "",
  "Right-to-try laws (federal version signed in 2018) allow terminally ill patients to request access to investigational drugs that have completed Phase I safety trials but haven't finished the full FDA approval process. Supporters argue it respects patient autonomy and offers hope; critics worry it may expose desperate patients to ineffective or harmful treatments, and that it undermines the clinical trial system designed to protect patients.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company develops a technique to select embryos for intelligence-enhancing genes. Parents begin requesting 'designer baby' packages. Which bioethical principle is MOST directly challenged, and why might this create a 'genetic divide' in society?": "",
  "Nonmaleficence — genetic selection never causes any physical harm": "",
  "Beneficence only — enhancing intelligence always benefits the child with no downsides": "",
  "Justice — wealthy families could gain permanent genetic advantages unavailable to others, creating a biological class system across generations": "",
  "The free market should determine who receives genetic enhancements": "",
  "Designer babies raise profound justice and equity concerns. If genetic enhancements are expensive, only wealthy families would access them — creating a 'genetic divide' where enhanced children have biological advantages in intelligence, health, and lifespan. Over generations, this could produce a permanent biological underclass. The film 'Gattaca' explores this dystopia. Additionally, 'enhancement' vs. 'therapy' is a blurry line: fixing a disease gene is broadly accepted, but boosting traits beyond normal range raises questions about what it means to be human.": "",
  "A 23andMe-style genetic test reveals that a job applicant carries the BRCA1 mutation for breast cancer. The employer denies the position based on this information. Under U.S. law, what protections exist, and what gaps remain?": "",
  "No U.S. law addresses genetic discrimination in any context": "",
  "The ADA covers all genetic conditions, including predispositions without symptoms": "",
  "GINA (2008) prohibits genetic discrimination in health insurance and employment, but does NOT cover life insurance, disability insurance, or long-term care insurance": "",
  "HIPAA provides complete protection against all forms of genetic discrimination": "",
  "GINA's Title II specifically prohibits employers from using genetic information in hiring, firing, or promotion. However, GINA has significant gaps: it doesn't cover the military, companies with fewer than 15 employees, or life/disability/long-term care insurance. The ADA only covers individuals with existing disabilities, not genetic predispositions. As genetic testing becomes cheaper and more widespread, these gaps create ongoing policy debates.": "",
  "Researchers propose using CRISPR to edit human germline cells to eliminate sickle cell disease permanently from a family line. A bioethics committee raises the concern of 'consent across generations.' Explain the ethical dilemma and one potential unintended consequence.": "",
  "Sickle cell disease is too mild to justify any genetic intervention": "",
  "Germline editing has been proven completely safe with no off-target effects": "",
  "Germline edits are heritable and permanent — all future descendants inherit the change without consent, and off-target CRISPR effects could introduce harmful mutations propagating through generations": "",
  "CRISPR germline editing only affects the treated individual and cannot be passed to offspring": "",
  "The sickle cell case is compelling because it causes severe suffering. However, germline editing raises unique ethical concerns: (1) Future descendants cannot consent — the genetic change is permanent and irreversible across all subsequent generations. (2) Off-target effects: CRISPR may cut at unintended genomic sites, potentially creating new pathogenic mutations that are also heritable. (3) The sickle cell trait (one copy) actually confers malaria resistance — eliminating it entirely could remove this protective advantage in malaria-endemic regions. This illustrates the complexity of 'correcting' human genetics.": "",
  "A hospital has one available kidney for transplant. Patient A is 25 years old with no other health issues. Patient B is 65 years old but has been on the waiting list 5 years longer. An ethics board must decide. Compare two allocation principles and explain the real-world system.": "",
  "A random lottery is the only ethical way to distribute organs, removing all medical judgment from the decision": "",
  "The wealthiest patient should receive the organ because they can pay more for post-transplant medical care": "",
  "Organs are always given to the youngest patient regardless of waiting time, medical urgency, or tissue match": "",
  "First-come, first-served favors Patient B (fairness through waiting time); utilitarian maximum life-years favors Patient A; UNOS uses a complex formula balancing medical urgency, compatibility, waiting time, and geography": "",
  "Organ allocation involves competing ethical principles. First-come, first-served (deontological fairness) rewards patience but may waste organs on patients with shorter remaining lifespans. Utilitarian approaches maximize total life-years saved but could systematically disadvantage older or sicker patients. UNOS (United Network for Organ Sharing) balances multiple factors: medical urgency, blood/tissue compatibility, time on waiting list, geographic proximity, and organ size matching. Over 100,000 Americans are currently on transplant waiting lists.": "",
  "Scientists discover that embryonic stem cells (ESCs) can differentiate into any cell type, potentially curing Parkinson's disease. However, harvesting ESCs requires destroying 5-day-old blastocysts. Analyze the ethical tension and describe one alternative approach.": "",
  "The only ethical approach is to ban all stem cell research permanently": "",
  "Adult stem cells work identically to ESCs for all conditions, making ESC research unnecessary": "",
  "The tension is between medical potential (curing disease) and the moral status of embryos; iPSCs (induced pluripotent stem cells) offer a partial ethical alternative by reprogramming adult cells to a stem-cell state": "",
  "There is no ethical tension because blastocysts are not considered living by any ethical framework": "",
  "The ESC debate centers on the moral status of a 5-day-old blastocyst (~100 undifferentiated cells). Those who believe personhood begins at conception consider destroying blastocysts morally equivalent to ending a life. Those who prioritize medical benefits argue that blastocysts lack sentience, a nervous system, or the capacity to suffer. iPSCs (developed by Shinya Yamanaka, Nobel Prize 2012) reprogram adult somatic cells back to a pluripotent state, avoiding embryo destruction. However, iPSCs may not be identical to ESCs in all therapeutic applications.": "",
  "A clinical trial for a new cancer drug enrolls an 85-year-old with mild cognitive impairment. The research team obtains consent from the patient. An IRB member questions whether the consent is truly valid. What safeguards should be implemented?": "",
  "Elderly patients with any cognitive impairment should be automatically excluded from all research": "",
  "Cognitive tests are unnecessary — willingness to sign proves comprehension": "",
  "A formal capacity assessment, appointment of a legally authorized representative, simplified consent materials, and ongoing monitoring for continued comprehension": "",
  "The patient's signature alone is always sufficient regardless of cognitive status": "",
  "Informed consent requires comprehension, voluntariness, and capacity. Mild cognitive impairment doesn't automatically disqualify participation, but additional safeguards are needed: (1) Formal capacity assessment (e.g., MacArthur Competence Assessment Tool); (2) Legally authorized representative to co-consent and advocate; (3) Simplified consent documents with plain language and visual aids; (4) Teach-back method — asking the patient to explain the study in their own words; (5) Ongoing consent monitoring since cognitive status can fluctuate.": "",
  "In 2018, He Jiankui used CRISPR to edit the CCR5 gene in human embryos, creating the first gene-edited babies (Lulu and Nana) with claimed HIV resistance. The scientific community condemned this act. Analyze three specific ethical violations in this case.": "",
  "He bypassed proper ethical review (no legitimate IRB approval), violated the scientific moratorium on human germline editing, and obtained questionable consent from HIV-positive parents who may have felt coerced": "",
  "He's only violation was failing to publish his results in a peer-reviewed journal": "",
  "The scientific community supported He's work but was concerned about intellectual property": "",
  "CRISPR editing of CCR5 was proven completely safe before He's experiment": "",
  "He Jiankui's case violated multiple ethical norms: (1) No legitimate IRB oversight — he fabricated ethics approval documents; (2) Violated the international moratorium on clinical human germline editing; (3) Questionable consent — the HIV-positive father may have been desperate; (4) Premature technology — CRISPR introduced mosaicism (not all cells were edited); (5) Unnecessary risk — the father's HIV was controlled, and sperm washing could have prevented transmission; (6) CCR5-delta32 deletion may increase susceptibility to West Nile virus. He was sentenced to 3 years in prison and fined 3 million yuan.": "",
  "A country mandates that all newborns have their DNA sequenced and stored in a government database for 'public health purposes.' Evaluate the strongest arguments FOR and AGAINST this policy.": "",
  "Only arguments against exist — genetic screening never benefits anyone": "",
  "FOR: Early detection of treatable genetic conditions could save lives; AGAINST: Mass genetic databases can be misused for surveillance, discrimination, and data breaches that expose an entire population's most private information": "",
  "There are only arguments in favor — universal genetic screening has no downsides": "",
  "DNA sequencing technology is unreliable and would provide no useful health information": "",
  "Arguments FOR: newborn genetic screening could identify PKU, cystic fibrosis, sickle cell disease, and hundreds of other treatable conditions early, saving lives and reducing healthcare costs. Population-level data could accelerate genomic research. Arguments AGAINST: Government access to DNA enables surveillance and profiling; data breaches could expose millions' genetic information; genetic determinism could lead to discrimination; it violates reproductive privacy and the 'right not to know.' Countries like Iceland have voluntary databases, but mandatory ones raise serious civil liberties concerns.": "",
  "The Tuskegee Syphilis Study (1932–1972) left 399 African American men untreated for syphilis, even after penicillin became available. Explain how this study violated each of the three Belmont Report principles.": "",
  "The Belmont Report was written before the Tuskegee study occurred and therefore could not address its violations": "",
  "Participants fully understood and consented to all aspects of the study after receiving detailed written disclosures": "",
  "The study only violated one minor ethical guideline that has since been updated to reflect modern research standards": "",
  "Respect for persons: no informed consent was obtained and participants were actively deceived; Beneficence: treatment was deliberately withheld causing preventable suffering and death; Justice: a vulnerable racial minority bore the entire research burden for society's benefit": "",
  "The Tuskegee study systematically violated all three Belmont principles: (1) RESPECT FOR PERSONS: Men were told they were receiving 'free treatment for bad blood' — a lie. They were never told they had syphilis and never consented to being studied without treatment. (2) BENEFICENCE: Even after penicillin became standard treatment in 1947, researchers actively prevented participants from receiving it elsewhere, causing preventable blindness, insanity, and death. (3) JUSTICE: The study exclusively targeted poor, uneducated Black sharecroppers — a vulnerable population that bore all research risks while the benefits (medical knowledge) went to society at large. The exposure led to the Belmont Report (1979), the establishment of IRBs, and a formal presidential apology in 1997.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company runs an HIV drug trial in a developing country where participants currently receive no treatment. The company argues this is ethical because participants receive a potentially beneficial experimental drug. Critics argue the control group should receive the best available worldwide treatment, not a placebo. Analyze both positions using the principles of justice and beneficence.": "",
  "Any experimental drug is automatically better than no treatment, so there are no ethical concerns": "",
  "Justice requires that the control group receive the best proven worldwide treatment (Declaration of Helsinki standard), not just the local 'no treatment' standard; critics say using local standards exploits desperate populations who can't access the final product": "",
  "Clinical trials in developing countries are always ethical because participants get free healthcare": "",
  "The company should only conduct trials in wealthy countries where regulations are stricter": "",
  "This scenario reflects a real and ongoing debate. The Declaration of Helsinki (Article 33) states that even placebo-controlled trials must provide the best proven treatment, not just local standard care. JUSTICE argument: Conducting trials in places with no care access exploits desperation; if the drug succeeds, it may be priced beyond the host country's reach. BENEFICENCE argument: Even a placebo-controlled trial gives participants medical monitoring they wouldn't otherwise receive. The counterargument: this reasoning could justify any exploitation because 'some benefit is better than none.' The 1997 AZT trials in Africa crystallized this debate — pregnant women received short-course AZT or placebo rather than the full regimen available in wealthy countries.": ""
}